content.text: # db-ux-design-system/core-web/docs Documentation Below is a structured llms.txt index of Markdown files extracted from the /docs folder. Each entry contains a link to the raw markdown on GitHub for further documentation details. ## Root Files - [adr-04-icons.md](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/main/docs/adr-04-icons.md): Handling Functional Icons in Design System This document outlines the approach to handling functional icons in the design system, focusing on providing flexibility for consuming developers. It suggests using both SVG files and icon fonts, with a preference for icon fonts to simplify asset referencing. The approach involves using SCSS mixins to separate markup from styling and ensure non-breaking update feasibility. For icons set by the user, it recommends using either SCSS mixins or HTML attributes. The goal is to provide a clear and maintainable way to handle functional icons. Example usage of SCSS mixin for setting icons: ```scss // Using SCSS mixin for setting icons .icon-example { @include icon-font('example-icon'); } ``` Example usage of HTML attribute for setting icons: ```html ``` Additional examples in the document include using icon fonts and SVG files. KEY TECHNICAL TERMS: 1. SCSS mixin 2. Icon fonts 3. SVG files 4. Functional icons 5. Non-breaking update feasibility 6. Asset referencing 7. HTML attribute `data-icon` 8. Design system 9. Consuming developers 10. Flexibility - [conventions.md](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/main/docs/conventions.md): Git Commits and Code Conventions for db-ux-design-system This document outlines the Git commit conventions and code conventions for the db-ux-design-system/core-web repository. It uses husky git hooks and commitlint to enforce commit message formatting, with a specified type and scope. The commit message format is `type(scope?): subject`, with an optional body and footer. The document also mentions code conventions ensured by configuration files `.editorconfig` and `.gitattributes`, as well as tools like xo, prettier, and commitlint. For example, to test a commit message, you can use the command `echo 'foo: bar' | commitlint`. The document provides a list of allowed types for commit messages, including build, chore, ci, docs, feat, fix, perf, refactor, revert, style, and test. Example commit message format: ```text type(scope?): subject body? footer? ``` Example usage of commitlint: ```terminal echo 'foo: bar' | commitlint ``` Note that there are additional code examples in the document, including configurations for `.editorconfig` and `.gitattributes`. KEY TECHNICAL TERMS: * commitlint * husky git hooks * commit message format * code conventions * xo * prettier * .editorconfig * .gitattributes * Git commit conventions * commit message types (build, chore, ci, docs, feat, fix, perf, refactor, revert, style, test) - [definition-of-done-pr.md](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/main/docs/definition-of-done-pr.md): Definition of Done for Pull Requests This document outlines the definition of done for pull requests in the db-ux-design-system/core-web repository. It emphasizes the importance of reviewing changes before merging, including updating migration documentation and thoroughly checking the "Files changed" tab on GitHub. The document provides guidelines for contributors to ensure that their pull requests are complete and follow the necessary steps. Key steps include adding new files or entries to the next release in the `/docs/migration` folder and conducting a final review of changes. Example: - Update [`/docs/migration`](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/tree/main/docs/migration) folder. Additional code examples: None. KEY TECHNICAL TERMS: - Pull Requests - Migration documentation - GitHub - Release notes - Code changes - Consuming packages - TODOs - Migration folder - [development.md](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/main/docs/development.md): Development and Testing Setup for DB-UX Design System This document outlines the development and testing setup for the DB-UX Design System, including environmental variable setup, installation, building, and testing procedures. To start developing, insert environmental variables as described in the `@db-ux/db-theme` package, then run `npm install`, `npm run build`, and `npm run start`. The document also covers visual regression testing using Playwright, including regenerating screenshots and updating snapshots. Additionally, it provides instructions for manual testing and updating screenshots using Docker. Example code: ```shell npm install npm run build npm run start ``` Note: There are additional code examples for Docker and docker-compose usage. KEY TECHNICAL TERMS: * Playwright * Visual regression tests * Docker * npm * Environmental variables * DB-UX Design System * CI/CD * Git commits conventions * Snapshots * Component tests - [how-to-develop-a-component.md](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/main/docs/how-to-develop-a-component.md): Developing a Component with DB UX Design System This document outlines the steps to develop a component using the DB UX Design System, including generating required files, starting development, styling with SCSS, defining the component API, coding the component, testing with frameworks, and writing tests for quality assurance. The guide covers component structure, styling, and testing for multiple frameworks, including Angular, React, and Vue. It also touches on accessibility testing and manual audits. To generate a component, run `npm run generate:component` and follow the prompts. The main work for the component will be inside `packages/components/src/components/my-awesome-component`. For styling, use SCSS and leverage variables from `@db-ux/core-foundations/build/styles/variables`. Example of using variables and styling: ```scss @use "@db-ux/core-foundations/build/styles/variables"; @include variables.$db-spacing-fixed-md; ``` When coding the component, use Mitosis and define properties in `model.ts`. For example: ```typescript export type DBMyAwesomeComponentProps = DBMyAwesomeComponentDefaultProps & WidthProps; ``` The document also provides information on testing with multiple frameworks and writing tests for quality assurance. Additional code examples include defining component properties and states in `model.ts` and using Mitosis for component development. KEY TECHNICAL TERMS: 1. Mitosis 2. SCSS 3. DB UX Design System 4. This decision was made to reduce the time spent writing components for each framework and to provide a good developer experience. Response.content:
Now let me gather more information about your specific requirements for the todo app:

Based on my exploration of the DB UI components documentation, I've discovered that:

**Available DB UI Components for our todo app:**
- **DBButton** - For actions like "Add Todo", "Delete", "Edit"
- **DBInput** - For entering new todo items
- **DBCheckbox** - For marking todos as complete/incomplete

**Key Technical Findings:**
- DB UI uses Mitosis to generate native Vue.js components (not web components)
- Components follow Deutsche Bahn design guidelines and accessibility standards
- The system supports Vue.js with proper TypeScript integration

**Questions to help define the scope:**

1. **Todo Features**: What specific features do you want in the todo app?
   - Add new todos
   - Mark todos as complete/incomplete
   - Delete todos
   - Edit existing todos
   - Filter todos (all/active/completed)
   - Clear completed todos

2. **Data Structure**: What information should each todo contain?
   - Just text content?
   - Priority levels?
   - Due dates?
   - Categories/tags?

3. **UI Layout**: Any specific layout preferences?
   - Single page with all todos listed?
   - Any specific sections or groupings?

4. **Local Storage**: How should we structure the data in local storage?
   - Simple array of todos?
   - More complex structure with metadata?

Let me know your preferences for these aspects, and I can continue exploring the technical implementation details and move toward the planning phase.

Prompt.prompt:
1. all of them
2. all of them
3. single list, no groups
4. let's use indexdb and a relational model (items, tags)

ToolUse.content: Perfect! Thank you for the clarifications. Let me update the plan with these requirements and continue exploring the technical implementation details.

args.new_str:
## Goal
Build a comprehensive todo app using Vue.js with DB UI components for styling, using IndexedDB with a relational model (items, tags) for data persistence (no backend required).

**Features:**
- Add new todos
- Mark todos as complete/incomplete  
- Delete todos
- Edit existing todos
- Filter todos (all/active/completed)
- Clear completed todos
- Priority levels
- Due dates
- Categories/tags

**Data Model:**
- Items table: id, text, completed, priority, dueDate, createdAt, updatedAt
- Tags table: id, name, color
- ItemTags junction table: itemId, tagId

**UI Layout:**
- Single page with all todos in one list (no groupings)

Perfect! Let me continue exploring the remaining technical aspects. I need to research IndexedDB libraries, Vue.js project setup, and other implementation details.

**IndexedDB Implementation Research:**

For IndexedDB with a relational model, I recommend using **Dexie.js** - it's a wrapper around IndexedDB that makes it much easier to work with relational data patterns. Here's why:

1. **Dexie.js Benefits:**
   - Simplified API for complex queries
   - Built-in support for relationships and joins
   - TypeScript support
   - Promise-based (works well with Vue 3 Composition API)
   - Good performance with large datasets

2. **Alternative Options:**
   - **idb** - Lighter weight but more manual work for relationships
   - **PouchDB** - More complex, designed for sync scenarios
   - **Native IndexedDB** - Too complex for relational patterns

**Vue.js Project Setup Questions:**

1. **Vue Version**: Should we use Vue 3 (recommended) with Composition API?
2. **Build Tool**: Vite (modern, fast) or Webpack?
3. **TypeScript**: Do you want TypeScript support for better type safety?
4. **State Management**: Do you prefer Pinia (Vue 3 recommended) or Vuex?
5. **CSS Framework**: Just DB UI components or additional utility classes?

**DB UI Installation Questions:**

Looking at the DB UI documentation, I need to understand:
1. **Package Installation**: Which specific DB UI packages do we need?
2. **Theme Setup**: How to configure DB UI theming in Vue.js?
3. **Icon System**: How to integrate DB UI icons for todo actions?

**Date Handling for Due Dates:**

Since I couldn't find a specific DB UI date picker component, we have options:
1. **Native HTML5**: `<input type="date">` styled with DB UI classes
2. **Third-party**: Vue-compatible date picker styled to match DB UI
3. **Simple Text Input**: For basic date entry with validation

**Tag/Chip Implementation:**

For the tag system, we could:
1. **Custom Component**: Build tags using DB UI button/badge styling
2. **Third-party**: Vue tag input component styled with DB UI
3. **Simple Select**: Use DBSelect for predefined tags

**Questions for you:**

1. **Vue Version & Setup**: Vue 3 with Vite and TypeScript?
2. **State Management**: Pinia for managing todo state?
3. **Date Input**: Are you okay with native HTML5 date input, or do you want a more sophisticated date picker?
4. **Tag UX**: Should users be able to create new tags on-the-fly, or select from predefined tags?
5. **Priority Levels**: How many priority levels? (e.g., Low, Medium, High, Critical)

Let me know your preferences on these technical decisions, and I can continue exploring the specific implementation details!

- **Features**: Full-featured todo app with priorities, due dates, tags, and filtering
- **UI Layout**: Single page with unified todo list (no groupings)
- **Date Input**: Native HTML5 date input styled with DB UI classes
- **Tag System**: Create new tags on-the-fly + select from existing tags

## Query

Vue installation setup package.json npm install.

## Response

### Sources:
Important: you can fetch the full content of any source using the fetch_url_content tool

#### (db-ux-design-system/core-web/README.md)[https://raw.githubusercontent.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/main/README.md] (Score: 0.52)
- Packages

| Package                                                                                         | Content                             | Version                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            |
| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| [foundations](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/tree/main/packages/foundations)   | CSS/SCSS/Tailwind styles and assets | [![@db-ux/core-foundations on Npmjs](https://img.shields.io/badge/dynamic/json?url=https%3A%2F%2Fapi.github.com%2Frepos%2Fdb-ux-design-system%2Fcore-web%2Freleases%2Flatest&query=%24.tag_name&label=npm&color=ed1c24 "npm version")](https://npmjs.com/package/@db-ux/core-foundations "DB UX Design System – on NPM")           |
| [components](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/tree/main/packages/components)     | CSS/SCSS styles for components      | [![@db-ux/core-components on Npmjs](https://img.shields.io/badge/dynamic/json?url=https%3A%2F%2Fapi.github.com%2Frepos%2Fdb-ux-design-system%2Fcore-web%2Freleases%2Flatest&query=%24.tag_name&label=npm&color=ed1c24 "npm version")](https://npmjs.com/package/@db-ux/core-components "DB UX Design System – on NPM")   
- �� on NPM")       |

## How to use

Install your preferred package via npm or yarn e.g. `npm i @db-ux/react-core-components`.

Afterwards you need to add the specific CSS or SCSS files to provide the styles of DB UX Design System (Version 3), as described in the "Styling Dependencies" of each packages `README`.
We even also provide some [examples of integrations](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/examples).

### DB Theme

In case that you're building a website or application for Deutsche Bahn, you'll additionally have to install the DB Theme via the [`@db-ux/db-theme`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@db-ux/db-theme) node package (even also available as an inner source node package, as described within that packages README).

## Components

We maintain a [status overview](https://github.com/orgs/db-ux-design-system/projects/4/views/1) f

#### (db-ux-design-system/core-web/docs/how-to-develop-a-component.md)[https://raw.githubusercontent.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/main/docs/how-to-develop-a-component.md] (Score: 0.48)
- 
## Start developing

- Your main work for the component will be inside `packages/components/src/components/my-awesome-component`.

- To develop on your component you can start a development server by running `npm run dev`, this will give you some options to choose from. When you begin "scribbling" (html+scss) with a component you can select `plain-html`. For _advanced users_ you can skip this and develop directly for one framework (html+scss+ts), see [Test Frameworks with Showcases](#test-frameworks-with-showcases).


- # How to develop a component

## Generate all required files

1. Run `npm run generate:component` in a terminal.

2. You should type in the name of your new component like `my-awesome-component` and answer everything with "yes".

3. The generation process will generate files mainly in these directories:

- `packages/components`
- `showcases`

## Start developing

- Your main work for the component will be inside `packages/components/src/components/my-awesome-component`.

- To develop on your component you can start a development server by running `npm run dev`, this will give you some options to choose from. When you begin "scribbling" (html+scss) with a component you can select `plain-html`. For _advanced users_ you can skip this and develop directly for one framework (html+scss+ts), see [Test Frameworks with Showcases](#test-frameworks-with-showcases).

### Styling with SCSS

Starting with `packages/components/src/components/my-awesome-component/my-awesome-component.scss` there are something you should know:

1. The most important dependency are the `variables` included via `@use "@db-ux/core-foundations/build/styles/variables";`. They enable you to use e.g. `$db-spacing-fixed-md` for paddings, margins etc.
2. A lot of times you have to force another `font-size` / `line-height`, you can do it with `@use "@db-ux/core-foundations/build/styles/density/font;` and the corresponding placeholder extend: `@extend %db-overwrite-font-size-sm;`.
3. Some components have an 'adaptive' styling. We exclude it in an own file `@use "@db-ux/core-components/build/scss/styles/component";` so you might use this dependency. As a reference look at another component e.g. [`packages/components/src/components/button/button.scss`](../packages/components/src/components/button/button.scss).
4. If you have to set a specific color (informational, warning, etc.) directly you can use `@use "@db-ux/core-foundations/build/styles/colors";`. You can take a look at the `notification` component for an example `packages/components/src/components/notification/notification.scss` you might use the `@each` to reduce the amount of code for color-variants.
5. To set a fixed icon you might use `@use "@db-ux/core-foundations/build/styles/icon/icons.helpers" as icons;` as dependency and e.g. `@include icons.icon("arrow_forward"), "after");`. For a dynamic icon you could prefer integrating it in HTML code with the `data-icon` attribute.

### Component structure with HTML

Besides of the `scss` you need to change the HTML code for your component. If you start with `plain-html` you can test your component inside `packages/components/src/components/my-awesome-component/index.html`; for _advanced_ users you can change the `jsx` directly inside `packages/components/src/components/my-awesome-component/my-awesome-component.lite.tsx`.

There are some things you have to know:

1. There are some reserved `data-*` attributes. For example `data-icon="xxx"` or `data-icon-after="xxx"` which will set an icon as `::before` / `::after` contents.
2. Moreover, there are some `data-*` attributes with the same meaning which we try to align across all components. For example `data-width` should be always `auto` or `full-width` to have the same possible options. We've additionally summarized those by providing models / types for these. For a closer look on this ask the Design Team for the glossary.
3. Try to use native HTML tags. For example if you have something like an Accordion use `<details><summary>`, so you would reduce the amount of custom JS/TS code for the components.

### Define the API in `model.ts`

If you're happy with the styling and your HTML code the next thing would be to define all possible properties for the component. - ## Development

### Start developing

You'll need to insert the environmental variables as described within the package [`@db-ux/db-theme`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@db-ux/db-theme) first of all.

Afterwards run the following commands:

```shell
npm install
npm run build
npm run start
```

Please mind the [conventions for git commits](/docs/conventions.md#user-content-git-commits-conventions).

### Versions

All versions in all `package.json` files are set to `0.0.0`, we change those during release process in CI/CD.

### Tests

TODO: Elaborate on testing setup

#### Component Tests

##### Visual regression tests

Playwright is used to create and compare screenshots of each individual component.

###### Pipeline generated images

On every fail of the visual regression tests in the Default pipeline, we're regenerating the snapshots as a `snapshot-*`-artifact. Please download these ones from the "Summary" page and commit the updated screenshots with `npm run commit:updated-snapshots` command from project root.

###### Manual update

To update screenshots just run the following (you need Docker installed and available on your shell):

```shell
npm run regenerate:screenshots
```

If you want to generate the screenshots manually, do the following:

```shell
npm run build

# unix
docker run --rm --network host -v $(pwd):/work/ -w /work/ -it mcr.microsoft.com/playwright:v1.30.0-focal /bin/bash

# windows - allow file sharing (windows pop up)
docker run --rm --network host -v ${PWD}:/work/ -w /work/ -it mcr.microsoft.com/playwright:v1.30.0-focal /bin/bash

npm install

cd output/${frameworkFolder}

npx playwright test --update-snapshots
```

You can also use `docker-compose` to test or regenerate screenshots.

- testing: `docker-compose -f ./e2e/docker-compose.yml up`
- update screenshots: `docker-compose -f ./e2e/docker-compose.regenerate.yml up`

The release management process for db-ux-design-system/core-web involves standardizing and tracking issues using semantic versioning wording in pull request titles, such as [`fix:`](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/blob/main/docs/conventions.md?plain=1#L11), [`refactor:`](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/blob/main/docs/conventions.md?plain=1#L11), and [`feat:`](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/blob/main/docs/conventions.md?plain=1#L11). Issues are managed through the [UX Engineering Team Backlog board](https://github.com/orgs/db-ux-design-system/projects/6/views/1), where their status is set to "ready for release" after review. A Release Manager oversees the process, ensuring all issues are ready for release and merging Pull Requests on release day. The scope of releases and candidates are also tracked across multiple repositories.

Example of semantic versioning wording: 
- [`fix:`](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/blob/main/docs/conventions.md?plain=1#L11) for bugfixes 
- [`refactor:`](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/blob/main/docs/conventions.md?plain=1#L11) or [`feat:`](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/blob/main/docs/conventions.md?plain=1#L11) for minor releases.

Additional code examples: There are references to GitHub project management and conventions.

This document outlines the migration steps from Beta 1.x.x to 2.0.0 of the db-ux-design-system/core-web repository. Key changes include updates to Tag and Batch components, Angular event alignment, and modifications to Foundation, such as replacing DB Screen fonts with DB Neo Screen and updating design tokens. The migration involves removing certain properties, renaming others, and introducing new variables. A CLI tool is provided to automate the migration process. 

For example, the Tag and Batch components no longer use the `origin` emphasis and now utilize `bg-vibrant` and `on-bg-vibrant` colors for the `strong` emphasis. 

```shell
npx @db-ux/core-migration --type=v100_v200 --src=./src
```

This command can be used to auto-migrate the source code. Additional code examples include changes to Angular events, such as replacing `onClick` with `click`.

There are also other code examples available, including design token updates and font changes.

6. bg-vibrant

8. signals

#### (db-ux-design-system/core-web/docs/development.md)[https://raw.githubusercontent.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web/main/docs/development.md] (Score: 0.52)
- ## Development

### Start developing

You'll need to insert the environmental variables as described within the package [`@db-ux/db-theme`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@db-ux/db-theme) first of all.

Afterwards run the following commands:

```shell
npm install
npm run build
npm run start
```

Please mind the [conventions for git commits](/docs/conventions.md#user-content-git-commits-conventions).

### Versions

All versions in all `package.json` files are set to `0.0.0`, we change those during release process in CI/CD.

### Tests

TODO: Elaborate on testing setup

#### Component Tests

##### Visual regression tests

Playwright is used to create and compare screenshots of each individual component.

###### Pipeline generated images

On every fail of the visual regression tests in the Default pipeline, we're regenerating the snapshots as a `snapshot-*`-artifact. Please download these ones from the "Summary" page and commit the updated screenshots with `npm run commit:updated-snapshots` command from project root.

###### Manual update

To update screenshots just run the following (you need Docker installed and available on your shell):

```shell
npm run regenerate:screenshots
```

If you want to generate the screenshots manually, do the following:

```shell
npm run build

# unix
docker run --rm --network host -v $(pwd):/work/ -w /work/ -it mcr.microsoft.com/playwright:v1.30.0-focal /bin/bash

# windows - allow file sharing (windows pop up)
docker run --rm --network host -v ${PWD}:/work/ -w /work/ -it mcr.microsoft.com/playwright:v1.30.0-focal /bin/bash

npm install

cd output/${frameworkFolder}

npx playwright test --update-snapshots
```

You can also use `docker-compose` to test or regenerate screenshots.

- testing: `docker-compose -f ./e2e/docker-compose.yml up`
- update screenshots: `docker-compose -f ./e2e/docker-compose.regenerate.yml up`

## Key Decisions
- **Framework**: Vue.js 3 with Composition API for the frontend framework
- **Build Tool**: Vite for fast development and building
- **TypeScript**: Yes, for better type safety and developer experience
- **State Management**: Pinia for managing todo application state
- **UI Components**: DB UI Design System components (DBButton, DBInput, DBCheckbox, DBSelect)
- **Data Storage**: IndexedDB with Dexie.js for relational model (items, tags, itemTags junction table)
- **Architecture**: DB UI uses Mitosis to generate native Vue components
- **Styling**: DB UI provides built-in styling following Deutsche Bahn design guidelines
- **Features**: Full-featured todo app with priorities, due dates, tags, and filtering
- **UI Layout**: Single page with unified todo list (no groupings)
- **Date Input**: Native HTML5 date input styled with DB UI classes
- **Tag System**: Create new tags on-the-fly + select from existing tags
- **Priority Levels**: Low, Medium, High, Critical
- **Database Schema**: TodoItem, Tag, ItemTag tables with proper relationships
- **Package Installation**: @db-ux/vue-core-components + foundations + db-theme

  ```
  1. App Load → Initialize Pinia store → Load todos/tags from IndexedDB
  2. Add Todo Flow:
     - User fills TodoForm (text, priority, due date, tags)
     - Form validation → Submit → Store action → DB save → UI update
  3. Edit Todo Flow:
     - Click edit → TodoItem becomes editable → Save/Cancel actions
  4. Complete Todo Flow:
     - Click checkbox → Toggle action → DB update → UI update
  5. Delete Todo Flow:
     - Click delete → Confirmation → Delete action → DB remove → UI update
  6. Filter Flow:
     - Click filter button → Update store filter → Computed todos update
  7. Tag Management Flow:
     - Create new tag → Add to available tags → Assign to todo
     - Select existing tag → Multi-select interface
  ```

  ```typescript
  // Input Validation
  - Todo text: Required, min 1 char, max 500 chars
  - Due date: Optional, must be future date or today
  - Tag name: Required, min 1 char, max 50 chars, unique
  - Priority: Must be valid enum value

  // Error Handling Layers
  1. Form Validation (Client-side)
     - Real-time validation with DB UI error states
     - Form submission prevention on invalid data
  
  2. Database Service (Service layer)
     - Try-catch blocks around all DB operations
     - Specific error types for different failures
     - Graceful degradation for DB connection issues
  
  3. Store Actions (State management)
     - Loading states during async operations
     - Error state management in store
     - User-friendly error messages
  
  4. Component Level (UI feedback)
     - Loading spinners during operations
     - Toast notifications for success/error
     - Fallback UI for error states
  ```

# @db-ux/v-core-components ![Apache 2.0 license badge](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache_2.0-blue.svg) [![code style: prettier](https://img.shields.io/badge/code_style-prettier-ff69b4.svg?style=flat-square)](https://github.com/prettier/prettier) [![Conventional Commits](https://img.shields.io/badge/Conventional%20Commits-1.0.0-yellow.svg)](https://conventionalcommits.org) [![PRs Welcome](https://img.shields.io/badge/PRs-welcome-brightgreen.svg?style=flat-square)](https://makeapullrequest.com) A Vue library containing all styles & components of [DB UX Design System (technical components)](https://github.com/db-ux-design-system/core-web). > **Note:** Find more information about specific components [here](https://design-system.deutschebahn.com/core-web/review/main) ## Install ```shell npm i @db-ux/v-core-components ``` > **Note:** This will install [`@db-ux/core-foundations`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@db-ux/core-foundations) and [`@db-ux/core-components`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@db-ux/core-components) as well which contains the `css`/`scss` files ## Styling Dependencies Import the styles in scss or css. Based on your technology the file names could be different. - Default (relative): points to `../assets` - Rollup (rollup): points to `@db-ux/core-foundations/assets` - Webpack (webpack): points to `~@db-ux/core-foundations/assets`
SCSS ```scss // style.scss @forward "@db-ux/core-components/build/styles/rollup"; ``` ```ts // main.ts import "./style.scss"; ```
CSS ```ts // main.ts import "@db-ux/core-components/build/styles/rollup.css"; ```

</details>

> **Note:** The `@db-ux/core-components/build/styles/relative` file contains optional and all components styles. If you consider performance issues see [@db-ux/core-components](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@db-ux/core-components) for more information.

### DB Theme

In case that you're building a website or application for Deutsche Bahn, you'll additionally have to install the DB Theme via the [`@db-ux/db-theme`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@db-ux/db-theme) node package (even also available as an inner source node package, as described within that packages README).

## Usage

```vue
<script setup lang="ts">
import { DBButton } from "@db-ux/v-core-components";
</script>

<template>
	<DBButton icon="x_placeholder">Test</DBButton>
</template>
```

### Events

We add `v-model` support which fires on every change.
But you can use normal `@` events as well.

Both Inputs in this example do the same:

```html
<script setup lang="ts">
	import { DbInput } from "@db-ux/v-core-components";
	import { ref } from "vue";
	const input = ref("");
</script>
<template>
	<DBInput
		label="Inputfield"
		name="input-name"
		v-model:value="input"
	></DBInput>
	<DBInput
		label="Inputfield"
		name="input-name"
		:value="input"
		@change="e => input = e.target.value"
	></DBInput>
</template>
```

## Deutsche Bahn brand

As we'd like to perfectly support our users and customers on their digital journey, the usage of Deutsche Bahn brand and trademarks are bound of clear guidelines and restrictions even if being used with the code that we're providing with this product; Deutsche Bahn fully reserves all rights regarding the Deutsche Bahn brand, even though that we're providing the code of DB UX Design System products free to use and release it under the Apache 2.0 license.

Perfect! Let me continue exploring the remaining technical aspects. I need to research IndexedDB libraries, Vue.js project setup, and other implementation details.

**IndexedDB Implementation Research:**

For IndexedDB with a relational model, I recommend using **Dexie.js** - it's a wrapper around IndexedDB that makes it much easier to work with relational data patterns. Here's why:

1. **Dexie.js Benefits:**
   - Simplified API for complex queries
   - Built-in support for relationships and joins
   - TypeScript support
   - Promise-based (works well with Vue 3 Composition API)
   - Good performance with large datasets

2. **Alternative Options:**
   - **idb** - Lighter weight but more manual work for relationships
   - **PouchDB** - More complex, designed for sync scenarios
   - **Native IndexedDB** - Too complex for relational patterns

**Vue.js Project Setup Questions:**

1. **Vue Version**: Should we use Vue 3 (recommended) with Composition API?
2. **Build Tool**: Vite (modern, fast) or Webpack?
3. **TypeScript**: Do you want TypeScript support for better type safety?
4. **State Management**: Do you prefer Pinia (Vue 3 recommended) or Vuex?
5. **CSS Framework**: Just DB UI components or additional utility classes?

3. **Simple Select**: Use DBSelect for predefined tags

ToolSpecification.name: fs_read
ToolSpecification.description:
Tool for reading files, directories and images. Always provide an 'operations' array.

For single operation: provide array with one element.
For batch operations: provide array with multiple elements.

Available modes:
- Line: Read lines from a file
- Directory: List directory contents
- Search: Search for patterns in files
- Image: Read and process images

Examples:
1. Single: {"operations": [{"mode": "Line", "path": "/file.txt"}]}
2. Batch: {"operations": [{"mode": "Line", "path": "/file1.txt"}, {"mode": "Search", "path": "/file2.txt", "pattern": "test"}]}

operations.description: Array of operations to execute. Provide one element for single operation, multiple for batch.

mode.description: The operation mode to run in: `Line`, `Directory`, `Search`. `Line` and `Search` are only for text files, and `Directory` is only for directories. `Image` is for image files, in this mode `image_paths` is required.

pattern.description: Pattern to search for (required, for Search mode). Case insensitive. The pattern matching is performed per line.

context_lines.description: Number of context lines around search results (optional, for Search mode)

image_paths.description: List of paths to the images. This is currently supported by the Image mode.

start_line.description: Starting line number (optional, for Line mode). A negative index represents a line number starting from the end of the file.

path.description: Path to the file or directory. The path should be absolute, or otherwise start with ~ for the user's home (required for Line, Directory, Search modes).

depth.description: Depth of a recursive directory listing (optional, for Directory mode)

end_line.description: Ending line number (optional, for Line mode). A negative index represents a line number starting from the end of the file.

summary.description: Optional description of the purpose of this batch operation (mainly useful for multiple operations)

ToolSpecification.name: fs_write
ToolSpecification.description:
A tool for creating and editing files
 * The `create` command will override the file at `path` if it already exists as a file, and otherwise create a new file
 * The `append` command will add content to the end of an existing file, automatically adding a newline if the file doesn't end with one. The file must exist.
 Notes for using the `str_replace` command:
 * The `old_str` parameter should match EXACTLY one or more consecutive lines from the original file. Be mindful of whitespaces!
 * If the `old_str` parameter is not unique in the file, the replacement will not be performed. Make sure to include enough context in `old_str` to make it unique
 * The `new_str` parameter should contain the edited lines that should replace the `old_str`.

insert_line.description: Required parameter of `insert` command. The `new_str` will be inserted AFTER the line `insert_line` of `path`.

new_str.description: Required parameter of `str_replace` command containing the new string. Required parameter of `insert` command containing the string to insert. Required parameter of `append` command containing the content to append to the file.

old_str.description: Required parameter of `str_replace` command containing the string in `path` to replace.

path.description: Absolute path to file or directory, e.g. `/repo/file.py` or `/repo`.

summary.description: A brief explanation of what the file change does or why it's being made.

command.description: The commands to run. Allowed options are: `create`, `str_replace`, `insert`, `append`.

file_text.description: Required parameter of `create` command, with the content of the file to be created.

profile_name.description: Optional: AWS profile name to use from ~/.aws/credentials. Defaults to default profile if not specified.

service_name.description: The name of the AWS service. If you want to query s3, you should use s3api if possible.

label.description: Human readable description of the api that is being called.

parameters.description: The parameters for the operation. The parameter keys MUST conform to the AWS CLI specification. You should prefer to use JSON Syntax over shorthand syntax wherever possible. For parameters that are booleans, prioritize using flags with no value. Denote these flags with flag names as key and an empty string as their value. You should also prefer kebab case.

operation_name.description: The name of the operation to perform.

region.description: Region name for calling the operation on AWS.

ToolSpecification.name: start_development
ToolSpecification.description: Begin a new development project with a structured workflow. Choose from different development approaches (waterfall, bugfix, epcc) or use a custom workflow. This tool sets up the project plan and initializes the development process.

require_reviews.description: Whether to require reviews before phase transitions. When enabled, use conduct_review tool before proceeding to next phase.

workflow.description:
Choose your development workflow:

• **bugfix**: bugfix - A focused workflow for bug fixing: Reproduce, Analyze, Fix, Verify - optimized for debugging and fixing existing issues
• **epcc**: epcc - A comprehensive development workflow based on Anthropic's best practices: Explore, Plan, Code, Commit - ideal for smaller features and iterative development
• **greenfield**: greenfield - A comprehensive workflow for starting new projects from scratch: Ideation, Architecture, Plan, Code, Document - ideal for greenfield projects requiring thorough upfront planning
• **minor**: minor - A streamlined workflow for small-impact changes: Explore (analysis + design) → Implement (code + test + commit) - optimized for minor enhancements
• **posts**: posts - A comprehensive workflow for writing posts - from blog posts to short-form content, with research, story development, and multi-platform publishing
• **slides**: slides - A comprehensive workflow for creating presentations - tool-agnostic approach that works with Slidev, PowerPoint, Google Slides, or any presentation platform
• **waterfall**: waterfall - From Specification down to test – the historical way. Ideal for larger, design-heavy tasks with well-defined requirements
• **custom**: Use custom workflow from .vibe/workflow.yaml in your project

Default: waterfall (recommended for larger, design-heavy tasks)

commit_behaviour.description: Git commit behavior: "step" (commit after each step), "phase" (commit before phase transitions), "end" (final commit only), "none" (no automatic commits). Use "end" unless the user specifically requests different behavior.
